Text.Value: Only one god empowered me to bring my Isobel back. That is the god I serve now. The god we serve.
Sorry about the cleric, but I'm here for an audience with the Absolute.
I thought you'd be angrier about my slaughter of your faithful.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Player has massacred Z'rell and others to get here.

Text.Value: You will listen. You will understand what you have cost me.
Death will only strengthen their faith, and you had no orders to spare them. Your orders were to retrieve Isobel.
Now she is Nightsong. Balthazar's greatest creation, and the source of my greatest strength.
But you - you have defied Her will and my orders. You were to report to Disciple Z'rell. You were to aid my cause! Instead you're here, showing your worthless face to me.
Make no mistake, that was always your fate. But I had hoped to make it painless.
Ironic, then, that it was Isobel who drove me into Shar's arms. She died, and I was left alone.
What can I do to atone for my failure?
Everything you've ever wanted.
You've had your indiscretions, but I find I can forgive a great deal in light of what you've done.
You had best dredge up some scrap of respect, True Soul. You will need it.

EditorData.NodeContext: furious, spitting vitriol

Text.Value: I can only wonder: why?
When she was killed, the man... he tried to remain whole, but it wasn't possible. Do you understand?
I am devoted to the Absolute.
She didn't want to be brought here, General. She fears you.
If that were true, the Selûnite cleric would be standing next to me right this moment. Instead, Disciple Z'rell is dead, and you - you're here, before me, for some unfathomable reason.

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt take: "If that were true, you would not bring chaos to my dominion. Disciple Z'rell is dead, and you have come to me empty-handed, and uninvited."

Text.Value: Isobel. You brought my daughter back to me.
From darkness into light. From oblivion back into her father's arms.
If that were true, you would have reported to Z'rell as you were told, you would have stayed off this roof as you were told, and you would be out there retrieving the Selûnite cleric!

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt true: "If that were true, you would have reported to Z'rell as instructed rather than interrupting a private ceremony."

Text.Value: I'll tell you a story, True Soul. About a man who sold himself piece by piece.
She wasn't overly keen on a reunion.
I'm not sure Isobel would see it that way.
You've travelled a long way to make it this far. Lied. Fought. Killed.
You're not like the others. Holy fervour does not motivate you. Nor does the promise of ultimate reward. How very sad for you.
That you have. That and more, True Soul.
I am ready to meet with the Absolute - if you'll permit it.
True Soul! I was so hoping to thank you in person.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Ketheric spots the player, opening his arms wide.
EditorData.NodeContext: Ketheric spots the player, opening his arms wide.

Text.Value: Go on. Now.

EditorData.NodeContext: Almost sarcastic, like a very annoyed child talking to their parent

Text.Value: So the man fell to pieces.
He could not break. His daughter needed him whole, after all.
What is this? I came to receive my audience with the Absolute.
How often our burdens can be made into boons, with the right encouragement.
Either go back out there and retrieve the cleric, or kneel at the altar. See if the Absolute cares to explain Herself to you.
I only hope your daughter can embrace the Absolute's will.
No.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: What of the Nightsong?
She was always stubborn. She clung to Selûne even after her mother's death.
I'm sure it was. Though I can't imagine convincing Isobel to come to the Towers was an easy feat.
You've travelled a long way to make it here. Lied. Fought. Killed - even those who would be your allies.
Vengeance is the best antidote to grief.
And yet Isobel - the Selûnite cleric - is nowhere to be found. Z'rell instructed you quite clearly.
The things we have done, True Soul.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slowly, in rising anger

Text.Value: I could ask the same of you.
She's your daughter, isn't she? Isobel Thorm. She fears you.
That is precisely why I sent you to retrieve her! She is lost. Confused. It is your holy duty to help me enlighten her.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shouting, the pinnacle of his rage.

Text.Value: Her hatred he could bear, perhaps, as long as she had another chance to live.
And the new god did as promised. The man's brilliant, beautiful daughter came back. She was whole - she was alive. But she despised the pitiful wretch her father had become.
So you understand what you have cost me, True Soul?
So you serve whichever god best serves you. A skewed philosophy.
What could the Absolute possibly want with the cleric?
Who are you to defy the Absolute's orders? My orders?
If that were true, the Selûnite cleric would be standing next to me right this moment. Z'rell gave you an order - an order on my behalf - and you failed it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt true: "If that were true, you would have delivered the Selunite cleric as Z'rell instructed you to do."

Text.Value: First, he sold himself to the goddess of loss. But the pain did not subside, no matter his obscene feats of devotion.
I want to see the truth of this god. What's next?
In the end, perhaps her death was a boon - an encouragement to point me toward our higher purpose.
I can. I will. But it is not without cost. Who will pay this time, True Soul?
You're wrong. But you'll discover that for yourself, when you meet the Absolute.
Never.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: He would have to give everything: his body and soul entire. He did not hesitate. Not for a moment.
The Absolute will decide your fate.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dismissive, like an extremely disappointed parent

Text.Value: No one of sound mind can look at what the Absolute offers and resist.
You think to take Isobel from me again? Why, True Soul? Why come here just to die?

EditorData.NodeContext: Pre combat, Ketheric is about to fight the player.

Text.Value: Half marks means you fail, True Soul.
It was an honour to serve, my lord.
I'd do whatever it takes to gain an audience with the Absolute.
You played your part. Don't spurn your reward just as you've earned it.
Everything I've done, everything I have built, has been to give Isobel that chance. And you, True Soul - you have squandered it.
I've retrieved my daughter's body - the one you so ruthlessly injured. She will live again. I want you to pay for what you've done.
My motivations are clear, aren't they? I serve the Absolute.
Our forces are gathered, the Nightsong bound, and we are ready to march at last. But most importantly...
Not my judgement. Be glad for that, True Soul.
Every god I have served, I have served in my daughter's name. And it almost came to nothing because of you.
I pledged my body and soul entire to a new god: a god who promised me my daughter could be returned to me.
As is your due.
She opposed the Absolute. Why mourn her?
I made perfect prey for Lady Loss. She promised vengeance. Oblivion. But her plans came to naught.
Indeed, I'd have thrown you off this tower by now if I didn't want to have a little chat first.
I have no mercy left in me - but it is for the Absolute to decide your fate.

EditorData.NodeContext: Almost sarcastic, like a very annoyed child talking to their parent

Text.Value: She grew up - grew strong. Challenged him. Filled his heart with such joy it supplanted all sorrow.
And I've served well. I've come to claim my reward.
You're Isobel's father? She wasn't overly keen on a reunion.
Does it matter? No sad story can undo the things you've done.
Taking Isobel was a mistake. I've come here to correct it.
I've heard a great deal about you, True Soul.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: NS captured but Isobel not captured
EditorData.logicalname: ISOBEL ALIVE/ NOT HERE; NS TRAPPED

Text.Value: The pain was unbearable. All-consuming. He decided he'd do anything for reprieve.
Kneel before the Absolute's altar. Throw yourself at Her mercy. Or try to earn Her forgiveness by retrieving the cleric Isobel. Your choice.
It is not for me to permit. You have earned this right.
But you - you have defied Her will. You failed to take Isobel - the Selûnite cleric. Indeed, True Soul, she is nowhere to be found.

EditorData.NodeContext: Crescendo of cold fury

Text.Value: I'll keep her close. Aylin was her name - an angel of Selûne's own brood, sent to guide and guard my line. Until she failed me.
A free tongue. You've earned that much, I suppose. But I do not have to explain myself.
Speaking of boons - I think I've earned one of my own.
I brought you the Nightsong - just as you asked.
You've travelled a long way to make it here. Lied. Fought. Even attacked me, who you ought to serve.
But you - you have defied Her will and my orders. Balthazar instructed you to retrieve the Selûnite cleric, but instead you are here questioning me!
He had... everything. A wonderful wife. A brilliant daughter. They lived not far from here.
You brought her back once. Do it again.
His wife died too young. Grief tore through their home like a thief, snatching away the scent of her hair, the rustle of her skirts. But the man did not break.
Every god you served granted you power in their way. Hardly a burden.
Not only do you fail to carry out your orders, but you wish to question the Absolute?
She's being introduced to the Absolute as we speak. Soon it will be as though we were never apart. You have our thanks for your part in our reunion.
Kneel at the altar. Now.
Indeed.

Text.Value: Farewell.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: But I know it wasn't easy for Isobel to accept how our family has changed.
It's subtle, but let me guess - the man is you.
Of course.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: Yes.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: Then a new god came - a god who promised the man something wonderful: his daughter. Her life returned. Imagine it.
So Isobel was dead, and you resurrected her?
I didn't know Isobel was your daughter, General. I submit myself to your judgement.
Always.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: Until the cleric is at my side, you are nothing. And you will be nothing until the Absolute cures you of the sin of your own mind.
It's time for you to learn true power. Make use of my own altar. Kneel in Her name, and the Absolute will come.
Perhaps.
